Re: ~対象とし、．．．~目標としている
by Michael_SD » Tue 03.01.2011 7:02 pm NileCat wrote:Sounds fine to me. It's good to hear such encouragement. I know translations/interpretations can often be worded a bit differently, as long as they convey the meaning of the original message. So, your response is welcome here. I had stagnated quite a while in learning Japanese, and have been on a learning plateau for quite a spell. Just recently I've decided to get restarted in earnest in learning the language again. Let me try the same thing! And…could you tell me if it sounds weird in English? I am not really sure, especially about the proper use of the articles and singular/plural forms. Also, I'd like to know if my choice of the subject is inappropriate. Thank you!This book is intended for intermediate-level learners of Japanese, and it aims at boosting their ability to an advanced level. Your sentence is perfectly understandable and grammatical. There is accurate concordance vis-a-vis singular and plural forms, articles, punctuation, and so forth. In particular, your correlation between "intermediate-level learners of Japanese" and "their ability" is fine. (For example, had you instead written, "for the intermediate-level learner of Japanese", "their ability" would change to "his or her ability".) So, you knew the correct agreement, and that's a good thing. One minor point I would want to make is that I think a better verb might be "raise" instead of "boost". But this is a question of style, not a question of semantics.Your English, frankly, is better than the English I have seen from native speakers of English in other fora.
Michael_SD
